16:41.100 --> 16:43.536 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Tonight, the focus is climate
change.

16:43.569 --> 16:48.574 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It is a subject that has gotten
very little
attention so far during the
campaign, even

16:48.608 --> 16:52.879 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
as it highlights one of the
starkest differences
between the candidates.

16:52.912 --> 16:55.014 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
William Brangham has our report.

16:55.047 --> 16:59.785 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: This past
weekend, the U.S.
and China officially ratified
the so-called

16:59.819 --> 17:01.587 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Paris climate accords.

17:01.621 --> 17:05.691 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They are the most substantial
move by the
world's nations to put some
limits on the

17:05.725 --> 17:09.896 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
greenhouse gas emissions that
are driving
global temperatures upwards.

17:09.929 --> 17:11.864 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And upwards, they keep going.

17:11.898 --> 17:16.669 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
2016 is on pace to be the
hottest year in
recorded history, breaking the
record set

17:16.702 --> 17:20.640 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
by 2015, and 2014 before that.

17:20.673 --> 17:25.244 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
As many climate models
predicted, a warming
planet has coincided with
increased heat waves

17:25.278 --> 17:28.247 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and droughts, as well as more
intense storms.

17:28.281 --> 17:32.852 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Glaciers and ice sheets continue
to shrink,
sending sea levels upwards and
threatening

17:32.885 --> 17:38.057 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
coastal communities all over the
world with
potentially catastrophic, costly
flooding.

17:38.090 --> 17:40.693 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Michael Oppenheimer is a climate
scientist
at Princeton University.

17:40.726 --> 17:44.797 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MICHAEL OPPENHEIMER, Princeton
University:
If we don't start with rapid
emissions reductions

17:44.830 --> 17:49.602 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and substantial emissions
reductions, that
we will pass a danger point,
beyond which

17:49.635 --> 17:55.207 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the consequences for many people
and countries
on Earth will simply become
unacceptable and

17:55.241 --> 17:56.943 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
eventually disastrous.

17:56.976 --> 18:01.113 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: But the Paris
accords only
set voluntary caps on carbon
emissions.

18:01.147 --> 18:05.284 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So how seriously the United
States follows
through on these commitments, as
well as its

18:05.318 --> 18:09.755 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
other efforts to curtail carbon,
will fall
largely on the next president.

18:09.789 --> 18:13.592 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And while there are plenty of
policies where
Clinton and Trump have different
views, there's

18:13.626 --> 18:18.064 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
probably no greater divergence
between them
than on the issue of climate
change.

18:18.097 --> 18:21.734 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
One thinks it is real and poses
a grave threat;
the other thinks it's a fantasy.

18:21.767 --> 18:24.403 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DONALD TRUMP (R), Presidential
Candidate:
I think it's a big scam for a
lot of people

18:24.437 --> 18:25.972 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to make a lot of money.

18:26.005 --> 18:28.908 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Donald Trump
has repeatedly
called climate change a hoax.

18:28.941 --> 18:33.546 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
He claims the planet is
freezing, and that
scientists are -- quote --
"stuck in ice."

18:33.579 --> 18:38.351 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Trump argues that environmental
regulation
is an enormous anti-competitive
tax on U.S.

18:38.384 --> 18:42.254 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
industry which also threatens
American jobs,
especially in the coal industry.

18:42.288 --> 18:45.424 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DONALD TRUMP: The federal
government, the
regulations that they have, they
put the coal

18:45.458 --> 18:46.892 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
miners out of business.

18:46.926 --> 18:48.761 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
The coal mines are shut.

18:48.794 --> 18:52.832 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: He says a
Trump administration
will undo as many regulations as
possible,

18:52.865 --> 18:57.670 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
starting with President Obama's
Clean Power
Plan, which has put limits on
coal emissions.

18:57.703 --> 19:02.108 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Trump has also promised to rip
up or cancel
the Paris accords, and block any
funding for

19:02.141 --> 19:04.276 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
international climate change
efforts.

19:04.310 --> 19:08.948 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He supports the expansion of
coal and oil
and natural gas as main energy
sources for

19:08.981 --> 19:10.883 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the United States.

19:10.916 --> 19:12.952 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HILLARY RODHAM CLINTON (D),
Presidential Candidate:
Climate change is such a
consequential crisis

19:12.985 --> 19:14.687 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to everybody in the world.

19:14.720 --> 19:17.456 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Hillary
Clinton, on the
other hand, has repeatedly
called climate

19:17.490 --> 19:21.894 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
change an urgent threat, and one
that is driven
in large part by human activity,
namely the

19:21.927 --> 19:23.863 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
burning of fossil fuels.

19:23.896 --> 19:28.000 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Clinton supports cutting carbon
emissions,
supports the goals of the Paris
accords, as

19:28.034 --> 19:30.903 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
well as President Obama's clean
energy plan.

19:30.936 --> 19:34.907 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Clinton acknowledges these plans
will cost
coal industry jobs, and she has
proposed a

19:34.940 --> 19:39.645 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
multibillion-dollar renewable
energy plan
that she says will attempt to
replace some

19:39.678 --> 19:41.380 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of those lost jobs.

19:41.414 --> 19:45.684 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
To help understand what a
Clinton or Trump
administration might mean with
regards to

19:45.718 --> 19:49.822 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
climate change, I'm joined now
by Coral Davenport,
who is an environmental reporter
for The New

19:49.855 --> 19:54.827 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
York Times, and Chris Mooney,
who covers science
and the environment for The
Washington Post.

19:54.860 --> 19:56.295 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Thank you both very much for
being here.

19:56.328 --> 19:58.064 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Chris, I would like to start
with you.

19:58.097 --> 20:01.500 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Before we get to the candidates,
let's talk
for a moment about, what does
the current

20:01.534 --> 20:05.371 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
science tell us about the
