of climate change?

20:05.404 --> 20:08.741 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHRIS MOONEY, The Washington
Post: Well, 2016
is a very, very hot year.

20:08.774 --> 20:14.747 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We're probably going to have
three hottest
year records in a row, 2014,
2015, 2016 topping

20:14.780 --> 20:16.715 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
them all.

20:16.749 --> 20:22.221 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we have seen some really
striking climate-related
effects on the world, most
starkly this year,

20:22.254 --> 20:25.458 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think, the bleaching of coral
reefs, big
disaster at the Great Barrier
Reef.

20:25.491 --> 20:28.494 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This is something that climate
scientists
have been predicting for a long
time, and

20:28.527 --> 20:29.662 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
now it's happening.

20:29.695 --> 20:31.530 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But there's all kinds of impacts
all around
the world.

20:31.564 --> 20:33.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We are losing more and more ice
from the polar
regions.

20:33.899 --> 20:35.000 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Seas are rising.

20:35.034 --> 20:37.603 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Of course, temperature records
are being broken.

20:37.636 --> 20:39.438 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Anything you
would add to
that, Coral?

20:39.472 --> 20:45.177 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CORAL DAVENPORT, The New York
Times: I would
just say, the specific sort of
marker that

20:45.211 --> 20:52.118 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
a lot of scientists and
scientific institutions
have put forth is the warming of
the atmosphere

20:52.151 --> 20:56.455 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
beyond 3.7 degrees Fahrenheit,
on average.

20:56.489 --> 21:00.693 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That's kind of the point at
which a lot of
scientists say we will be
irrevocably locked

21:00.726 --> 21:06.699 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
into a future of these climate
impacts, and
we're at the point right now
where scientists

21:06.732 --> 21:09.235 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
say a lot of that is already
baked in.

21:09.268 --> 21:10.703 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
There was a point...

21:10.736 --> 21:12.505 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: There's no way
we're going
to stop hitting that mark.

21:12.538 --> 21:14.273 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
CORAL DAVENPORT: Right.

21:14.306 --> 21:16.175 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There was a point in the climate
debate where
it was about, how do we keep
from getting

21:16.208 --> 21:18.010 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
there?

21:18.043 --> 21:22.381 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
At this point, in terms of the
emissions that
are already in the atmosphere
and the rate

21:22.414 --> 21:28.621 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of emissions now being produced
today, scientists
are saying, we're probably set
to go past

21:28.654 --> 21:30.289 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
that tipping point.

21:30.322 --> 21:35.194 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the debate is really about,
how do you
keep it from getting far, far
worse?

21:35.227 --> 21:37.997 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
How do you keep the planet
inhabitable by
humans?

21:38.030 --> 21:41.667 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: OK, staying
with you, I'm
going to put the crystal ball in
your hands

21:41.700 --> 21:42.668 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
now.

21:42.701 --> 21:44.236 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's January 2017.

21:44.270 --> 21:46.272 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Donald Trump is inaugurated
president.

21:46.305 --> 21:49.308 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What does U.S. energy policy and
climate change
policy look like?

21:49.341 --> 21:54.413 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CORAL DAVENPORT: Oh, well, the
most significant
climate policy that Donald Trump
has talked

21:54.446 --> 21:58.217 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
about is, he calls it canceling
the Paris
agreement.

21:58.250 --> 22:04.590 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Paris agreement was a
landmark accord
reached last year in Paris which
for the first

22:04.623 --> 22:11.030 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
time joined almost every country
on Earth,
over 195 countries, into
committing to taking

22:11.063 --> 22:15.501 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
actions to reducing their carbon
emissions.

22:15.534 --> 22:18.771 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It was key for the U.S. to be a
centerpiece
of that.

22:18.804 --> 22:26.178 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The U.S. and China are the
world's two largest
emitters of carbon emissions,
the U.S. historically

22:26.212 --> 22:27.980 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the largest.

22:28.013 --> 22:33.118 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If the U.S. actually were to
pull out of the
Paris agreement, the deal could
potentially

22:33.152 --> 22:34.887 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
unravel.

22:34.920 --> 22:40.893 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so the question now is, what
would happen
in a Trump administration?

22:40.926 --> 22:47.967 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the rest of the world, led
by U.N. Secretary-General
Ban Ki-Moon, is trying to kind
of figure out,

22:48.000 --> 22:53.939 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
well, how do we keep the Paris
accord intact
if there were to be a President
Trump?

22:53.973 --> 22:55.741 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Well, Chris,
take on that
question.

22:55.774 --> 23:00.846 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Does a president have the
ability, do they
have the levers to rip up the
Paris accords?

23:00.879 --> 23:05.918 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHRIS MOONEY: It depends what
happens during
this administration before the
next president

23:05.951 --> 23:07.686 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
comes in.

23:07.720 --> 23:11.290 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There is a sort of rapid push
right now by
the Obama administration and
many nations

23:11.323 --> 23:13.759 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of the world to bring it into
force.

23:13.792 --> 23:19.565 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And once it actually enters into
force, then
-- you have to have 55 countries
representing

23:19.598 --> 23:21.867 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
55 percent of the global
emissions in order
to achieve that.

23:21.900 --> 23:26.171 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Once that happens, there is
language in the
agreement saying you need three
years before

23:26.205 --> 23:27.273 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
you can withdraw again.

23:27.306 --> 23:29.074 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And then there's a year waiting
period.

23:29.108 --> 23:34.046 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So it sounds like, from that
language, the
hands of the next president
could be tied

23:34.079 --> 23:35.547 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
if this thing enters into force.

23:35.581 --> 23:37.283 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And we're going to have to see.

23:37.316 --> 23:41.620 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Right now, only about 40 percent
of global
emissions, 39 percent have
signed on, and

23:41.654 --> 23:43.255 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that's because U.S. and China
just did.

23:43.289 --> 23:47.059 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, you need India, you need
Canada, you need
Great Britain.

23:47.092 --> 23:51.964 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You can do the math, right, but
you have to
get to 55, and you have to do it
this year.

23:51.997 --> 23:54.667 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Then it would be more difficult
to withdraw.

23:54.700 --> 24:00.272 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But a President Trump, if he
didn't want to
comply, but couldn't make it go
away, could

24:00.306 --> 24:01.273 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
just not cooperate.

24:01.307 --> 24:03.042 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And it's not clear what would
happen then.

24:03.075 --> 24:06.145 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: All right,
crystal ball
is in your hands now.

24:06.178 --> 24:09.448 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
January 2017, Hillary Clinton is
inaugurated.

24:09.481 --> 24:11.283 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What does energy policy look
like?

24:11.317 --> 24:14.687 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHRIS MOONEY: I think it looks
like a pretty
strong continuation of Obama
climate policy.

24:14.720 --> 24:18.390 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think absolutely you would be
fulfilling
the Paris climate agreement and
trying to

24:18.424 --> 24:19.892 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
reduce U.S. emissions.

24:19.925 --> 24:25.130 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the goal is to get them 26
to 28 percent
below 2005 levels by 2025.

24:25.164 --> 24:28.233 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then there's going to be a
process where
we ratchet up and try to make it
even more

24:28.267 --> 24:29.601 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
ambitious.

24:29.635 --> 24:31.537 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I'm sure President Clinton would
be very much
on board with that.

24:31.570 --> 24:34.973 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think, domestically, one of
the most interesting
things that you would see under
President

24:35.007 --> 24:38.877 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Clinton is going to be the big
energy infrastructure
transition.

24:38.911 --> 24:40.813 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
How much solar can we install?

24:40.846 --> 24:42.848 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
How do we integrate it onto the
grid?

24:42.881 --> 24:45.784 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
How much of a role is natural
gas still playing
as coal dwindles?

24:45.818 --> 24:49.755 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Those are going to be the kind
of real issues
during the Clinton years that
are going to

24:49.788 --> 24:52.424 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
determine how much the United
States puts
into the atmosphere.

24:52.458 --> 24:55.527 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Coral, I know
you have been
following this somewhat.

24:55.561 --> 25:00.632 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Hillary Clinton got into some
trouble when
he said, as we make this push to
renewables,

25:00.666 --> 25:02.401 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
coal jobs are going to be lost.

25:02.434 --> 25:05.637 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, she has put out a big
proposal to say,
I'm going to beef up renewables,
we're going

25:05.671 --> 25:08.040 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to try to save some of those
jobs.

25:08.073 --> 25:09.908 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
How realistic is that?

25:09.942 --> 25:14.213 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
CORAL DAVENPORT: It's
interesting to see Hillary
Clinton, even if it didn't come
out quite

25:14.246 --> 25:20.486 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the way she meant it to, openly
acknowledge
that climate policy really does
direct take

25:20.519 --> 25:22.187 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
aim at coal.

25:22.221 --> 25:27.226 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Burning coal for electricity is
the largest
source of planet-warming
emissions in the

25:27.259 --> 25:28.894 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
U.S.

25:28.927 --> 25:32.030 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So if you're trying on stop
global warming,
you're going to take aim at
coal.

25:32.064 --> 25:37.136 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That means eventually the coal
community,
coal miners, the coal-fired
power plants,

25:37.169 --> 25:38.370 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
are going to get hurt.

25:38.404 --> 25:40.706 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Chris, last
question to
you.

25:40.739 --> 25:45.611 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The ability of a president to
really make
meaningful contributions to this
debate, if

25:45.644 --> 25:52.684 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
you were to go forward 50, 100,
150 years,
would we be able to tell the
difference between

25:52.718 --> 25:57.456 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a Clinton administration and a
Trump administration,
meaning, how much influence do
presidents

25:57.489 --> 26:01.160 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
really have on this policy when
we're talking
about a global problem?

26:01.193 --> 26:05.097 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHRIS MOONEY: Some significant
influence,
but I agree with you that there
are so many

26:05.130 --> 26:06.899 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
other things going on.

26:06.932 --> 26:11.003 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For instance, one of the reasons
the United
States has actually been
reducing its emissions

26:11.036 --> 26:14.339 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in recent years is actually that
there's been
a boom in natural gas.

26:14.373 --> 26:15.441 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's displacing coal.

26:15.474 --> 26:17.443 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It emits less carbon dioxide
when you burn
it.

26:17.476 --> 26:19.344 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
This is not really an Obama
policy.

26:19.378 --> 26:22.448 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
It's just something that
happened because
of technology and the free
market.

26:22.481 --> 26:28.053 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, globally, you're seeing a
big, big trend
towards large installations of
renewable energies

26:28.086 --> 26:29.721 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
across the world.

26:29.755 --> 26:33.125 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You are going to see huge
installations of
wind and solar in places like
Africa.

26:33.158 --> 26:35.027 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
These things are going to happen
no matter
what.

26:35.060 --> 26:39.198 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They're going to happen for
largely non-policy
free market reasons even in the
United States.

26:39.231 --> 26:43.569 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, I think that there are
forces moving that
are not really at the
presidential level.

26:43.602 --> 26:49.208 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, at the same time, the Obama
administration
kind of shows how you can use
diplomacy to

26:49.241 --> 26:51.977 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
bring the most important
countries together
and get the whole world on
board.

26:52.010 --> 26:54.379 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So I wouldn't discount that
either.

26:54.413 --> 26:58.851 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So I think that the world will
continue trying
to grapple with the climate
problem, no matter

26:58.884 --> 27:00.752 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
who is U.S. president.

27:00.786 --> 27:04.256 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I think that, depending on
who that president
is, it can have a significant
influence on

27:04.289 --> 27:06.024 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the trajectory.

27:06.058 --> 27:17.002 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: All right,
Chris Mooney,
Coral Davenport, thank you both
very much.

27:17.035 --> 27:21.173 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Stay with us.

27:21.206 --> 27:26.144 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Coming up on the "NewsHour": the
woman who
revitalized the traditional
textile industry

27:26.178 --> 27:32.184 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in Laos; and what social media
networks should
do to combat terrorism online.

27:32.217 --> 27:36.755 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But, first: a bloody year in
Chicago.

27:36.788 --> 27:42.194 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And residents, police and
community leaders
are asking why the violence is
getting worse,

27:42.227 --> 27:44.096 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
instead of better?

27:44.129 --> 27:51.036 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It is already the deadliest year
in more than
two decades, 500 homicides so
far, 90 in August

27:51.069 --> 27:52.437 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
alone.

27:52.471 --> 27:56.542 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
The killings were mostly
clustered on the
city's South and West Sides.

27:56.575 --> 28:02.681 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
John Yang went to Chicago to try
to find out
why, despite calls for new
action, the violence

28:02.714 --> 28:04.616 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
there is so hard to rein in.

28:04.650 --> 28:13.091 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: On this busy street
corner in Englewood,
one of the hardest-hit
neighborhoods on the

28:13.125 --> 28:16.061 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
city's troubled South Side, it
looks like
a party.

28:16.094 --> 28:18.363 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Kids are playing.

28:18.397 --> 28:20.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
The grill is fired up.

28:20.999 --> 28:25.837 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In the past, though, 75th and
Stewart felt
like a war zone.

28:25.871 --> 28:31.009 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TAMAR MANASSEH, Mothers Against
Senseless
Killings: This corner is a
corner where a

28:31.043 --> 28:33.078 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
man was killed -- well, several
men, a woman
was killed, and a child was
killed.

28:33.111 --> 28:36.615 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A 9-year-old girl was killed
right across
the street over there washing
her dog in broad

28:36.648 --> 28:38.483 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
daylight.

28:38.517 --> 28:43.088 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: But for two summers,
a group called
Mothers Against Senseless
Killings, or MASK,

28:43.121 --> 28:49.828 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
led by Tamar Manasseh, has been
out on this
corner, and there hasn't been a
single shooting.

28:49.861 --> 28:53.565 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Volunteer Laura Lambert (ph)
comes from nearby
Hyde Park.

28:53.599 --> 28:58.870 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And 91-year-old Edwina Knight
(ph) crosses
the street every day from the
house she's

28:58.904 --> 29:00.272 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
lived in for 57 years.

29:00.305 --> 29:01.640 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
TAMAR MANASSEH: Just show up.

29:01.673 --> 29:03.375 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That's all you have to do.

29:03.408 --> 29:07.479 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Show up, grab a lawn chair and a
pair of sunglasses,
and you can do this.

29:07.512 --> 29:09.281 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You can change the world with
that.

29:09.314 --> 29:16.688 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: But the moms of MASK
are only on
one corner in a city of 2.7
million people.

29:16.722 --> 29:19.091 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Killings have spiked this
summer.

29:19.124 --> 29:23.729 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Chicago has already recorded
more homicides
this year than it did in all of
last year.

29:23.762 --> 29:25.597 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

29:25.631 --> 29:26.531 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GARY SLUTKIN, University of
Illinois at Chicago:
This is also very typical of all
epidemics.

29:26.565 --> 29:29.001 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You can see the high density of
shootings.

29:29.034 --> 29:35.374 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JOHN YANG: University of
Illinois at Chicago
physician Gary Slutkin says
epidemic is exactly

29:35.407 --> 29:36.942 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the right word.

29:36.975 --> 29:40.078 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He argues that violence is a
contagious disease.

29:40.112 --> 29:41.747 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

29:41.780 --> 29:43.448 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GARY SLUTKIN: For example,
you're exposed
to flu, you're more likely to
get flu.

29:43.482 --> 29:46.118 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You don't actually get flu
without being exposed.

29:46.151 --> 29:48.587 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Same thing for T.B., cholera and
violence.

29:48.620 --> 29:52.724 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I mean, why does someone who was
exposed to
child abuse, abuse their own
kids?

29:52.758 --> 29:56.762 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That would be the person who you
would think
would be least likely to do it,
because he

29:56.795 --> 29:58.096 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
knows how bad it was.

29:58.130 --> 30:00.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But, in fact, he's picked up
this contagious
set of behaviors.

30:00.799 --> 30:06.038 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN YANG: So Dr. Slutkin treats
gun violence
as a contagious disease.

30:06.071 --> 30:11.576 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He founded Cure Violence, now an
international
effort that trains former gang
members and

30:11.610 --> 30:16.181 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
felons to stop violence in its
tracks, violence
interrupters.

30:16.214 --> 30:18.050 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

30:18.083 --> 30:22.721 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GARY SLUTKIN: They are always in
the community,
aware of what's going on, and
asking families

30:22.754 --> 30:25.023 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and people, you know, who's
upset?

30:25.057 --> 30:30.829 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You know, who is -- somebody
slept with someone's
girlfriend, someone was
disrespected, someone

30:30.862 --> 30:32.164 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
owes somebody money.

30:32.197 --> 30:35.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And we can reach those people
with these health
workers.

30:35.167 --> 30:37.669 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They may not look like health
workers to everybody.

30:37.703 --> 30:41.373 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They know how to cool people
down, know how
to buy time,

30:41.406 --> 30:47.079 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Chicago violence
interrupter Chico
Tillmon knows how to cool people
down.

30:47.112 --> 30:51.116 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He drove us around the South
Side last week,
where much of the violence
happens.

30:51.149 --> 30:55.454 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
CHICO TILLMON, Violence
Interrupter: In early
January, two cliques were
arguing.

30:55.487 --> 31:00.926 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So one clique went into another
clique's neighborhood
and got on Facebook Live and was
like: F.

31:00.959 --> 31:01.993 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
you all.

31:02.027 --> 31:03.628 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We're in your all neighbor.

31:03.662 --> 31:05.864 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We're in your all gas station.

31:05.897 --> 31:12.704 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Within 30 minutes, on that walk
from the gas
station back to the house, two
were dead,

31:12.738 --> 31:13.872 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
one was wounded.

31:13.905 --> 31:18.510 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN YANG: It's not like this is
a gang war
over turf.

31:18.543 --> 31:19.711 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
This is just sort of...

31:19.745 --> 31:21.646 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
CHICO TILLMON: Interpersonal.

31:21.680 --> 31:28.286 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I said something you didn't
agree with, you
responded negatively, it ended
up in gun violence.

31:28.320 --> 31:33.258 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Violence interrupter
Ulysses "U.S."
Floyd was a leader in one of
Chicago's most

31:33.291 --> 31:36.194 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
notorious gangs, the Gangster
Disciples.

31:36.228 --> 31:39.364 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ULYSSES "U.S." FLOYD, Violence
Interrupter:
I know I helped start this mess,
so I wanted

31:39.397 --> 31:40.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to help clean it up.

31:40.999 --> 31:44.803 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: He told us that gangs
are very
different now than they were in
his day.

31:44.836 --> 31:46.605 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ULYSSES "U.S." FLOYD: One or two
men control
everything.

31:46.638 --> 31:51.676 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now you have got a lot of
different little
gangs split all over.

31:51.710 --> 31:54.780 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They are offsprings of the major
gangs, what
they call cliques.

31:54.813 --> 31:56.948 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And they just do what they want
to do.

31:56.982 --> 31:59.818 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Ain't nobody really in control,
no structure,
no rules.

31:59.851 --> 32:03.822 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JOHN YANG: The number of
neighborhoods where
Chicago's branch of Cure
Violence operates

32:03.855 --> 32:05.991 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
varies based on funding.

32:06.024 --> 32:10.595 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But a Justice Department study
found that,
at one point, the group helped
reduce violence

32:10.629 --> 32:15.767 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
by 40 percent to 70 percent in
some of the
areas where they were operating.

32:15.801 --> 32:21.239 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Today, they are in only five of
the city's
77 neighborhoods.

32:21.273 --> 32:25.710 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
On our drive through the South
Side, we saw
children walking home from
school.

32:25.744 --> 32:27.913 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What do you think when you look
at kids that
age?

32:27.946 --> 32:34.019 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHICO TILLMON: I'm praying that
they survive
through this -- through this
epidemic that's

32:34.052 --> 32:36.521 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
going on in the city.

32:36.555 --> 32:37.989 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's not a Woodlawn problem.

32:38.023 --> 32:39.991 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's not a South Shore problem.

32:40.025 --> 32:41.960 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's everybody's problem.

32:41.993 --> 32:47.532 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we don't understand that
until the disease
hits home, until one of our
loved ones is

32:47.566 --> 32:48.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
killed by gun violence.

32:48.834 --> 32:50.402 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Then we want to get involved.

32:50.435 --> 32:54.506 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Police have seized
6,000 illegal
guns this year.

32:54.539 --> 33:00.512 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That's one every hour, many from
nearby Indiana,
where laws aren't as tough.

33:00.545 --> 33:06.284 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Chicago cops are feeling the
heat, a federal
probe of the use of deadly force
and public

33:06.318 --> 33:11.990 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
trust at a breaking point after
last year's
release of a dash-cam video
showing a white

33:12.023 --> 33:17.329 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
officer fatally shooting a black
teenager
16 times.

33:17.362 --> 33:22.234 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
After another deadly weekend,
Superintendent
Eddie Johnson virtually threw up
his hands.

33:22.267 --> 33:24.302 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
EDDIE JOHNSON, Chicago Police
Superintendent:
It's not a police issue.

33:24.336 --> 33:27.005 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's a society issue.

33:27.038 --> 33:30.775 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Impoverished neighborhoods,
people without
hope do these kinds of things.

33:30.809 --> 33:34.312 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You show me a man that doesn't
have hope,
I show you one that is willing
to pick up

33:34.346 --> 33:36.314 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
a gun and do anything with it.

33:36.348 --> 33:38.884 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LANCE WILLIAMS, Northeastern
Illinois University:
I really see this problem as a
cultural problem.

33:38.917 --> 33:43.555 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Lance Williams is an
associate
professor of urban affairs at
Northeastern

33:43.588 --> 33:46.558 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Illinois University and an
inner-city youth
advocate.

33:46.591 --> 33:48.460 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LANCE WILLIAMS: This is not a
law enforcement
problem.

33:48.493 --> 33:50.996 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I mean, you can hire all of the
police that
you want.

33:51.029 --> 33:57.335 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You're not going to solve this
problem, because
these young men are acting in
alignment with

33:57.369 --> 33:59.571 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
their cultural value system.

33:59.604 --> 34:02.340 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They need a cultural retooling
process.

34:02.374 --> 34:06.945 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Williams says it's a
culture that's
developed in the absence of
working institutions

34:06.978 --> 34:09.848 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and in the midst of crushing
poverty.

34:09.881 --> 34:13.251 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
One big cause of much
frustration?

34:13.285 --> 34:20.225 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Nearly half of black men in
Chicago aged 20
to 24 are not in school and out
of work, far

34:20.258 --> 34:22.928 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
higher than the national rate of
32 percent.

34:22.961 --> 34:25.263 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LANCE WILLIAMS: There's a lot of
rage.

34:25.297 --> 34:27.632 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
There's a lot of anger.

34:27.666 --> 34:30.402 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They just see their lives, you
know, just
passing them by.

34:30.435 --> 34:32.003 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They don't -- they haven't been
to school.

34:32.037 --> 34:33.738 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They're not qualified for jobs.

34:33.772 --> 34:37.776 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There are no viable businesses
in their neighborhood,
so they're really depressed.

34:37.809 --> 34:41.780 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And then they're self-medicating
through drinking
and drugging.

34:41.813 --> 34:48.553 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the only individuals around
them are other
young African-American males
like themselves

34:48.586 --> 34:50.855 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
who have these -- these same
forms of depression.

34:50.889 --> 34:56.428 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Another structural
factor playing
into the violence, Chicago is
one of the nation's

34:56.461 --> 34:58.296 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
most segregated cities.

34:58.330 --> 35:05.670 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LANCE WILLIAMS: All of the poor
blacks live
way, way, way, way away from
affluent people,

35:05.704 --> 35:09.040 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
from the business district, from
the tourist
district.

35:09.074 --> 35:12.444 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You know, you have some kids in
these neighborhoods
far south that have never been
downtown.

35:12.477 --> 35:14.145 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Right?

35:14.179 --> 35:17.949 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And you have folks in the white
communities
who have never been to the South
Side.

35:17.983 --> 35:21.219 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, what happens is, you have an
out-of-sight,
out-of-minute kind of deal.

35:21.252 --> 35:23.688 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
CHICO TILLMON: I was 23 when I
went to prison.

35:23.722 --> 35:30.362 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: For Chico Tillmon,
who spent 16
years and three months in
federal prison,

35:30.395 --> 35:36.634 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
violence is never out of sight
or mind, turning
other people's lives around
after turning

35:36.668 --> 35:38.436 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
his own around.

35:38.470 --> 35:43.441 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHICO TILLMON: Being able to see
all the violence
and chaos in the community that
I once was

35:43.475 --> 35:50.081 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a part of, and that I once
helped produce,
pushed me or gave me an
obligation to make

35:50.115 --> 35:51.082 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
a change.

35:51.116 --> 35:52.550 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Since you got out of
prison...

35:52.584 --> 35:53.585 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
CHICO TILLMON: Yes.

35:53.618 --> 35:54.619 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JOHN YANG: ... you got your
bachelor's degree.

35:54.652 --> 35:55.620 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
CHICO TILLMON: Yes, sir.

35:55.653 --> 35:56.821 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JOHN YANG: You got your master's
degree.

35:56.855 --> 35:57.822 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
CHICO TILLMON: Yes, sir.

35:57.856 --> 35:59.024 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JOHN YANG: You're working on
your Ph.D.

35:59.057 --> 36:00.392 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
CHICO TILLMON: Yes, sir.

36:00.425 --> 36:01.126 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN YANG: How long, how many
years are we
talking about here?

36:01.159 --> 36:02.761 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
CHICO TILLMON: Five years.

36:02.794 --> 36:04.396 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Pretty determined.

36:04.429 --> 36:05.397 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
CHICO TILLMON: Yes.

36:05.430 --> 36:06.431 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Pretty motivated.

36:06.464 --> 36:08.299 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
CHICO TILLMON: Yes, sir.

36:08.333 --> 36:15.340 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I got out with a purpose, and I
got out trying
to not only do something that
was beyond what

36:15.373 --> 36:19.544 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I believed I could do, but to
inspire hope
within all the people that I
left behind in

36:19.577 --> 36:21.212 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
prison.

36:21.246 --> 36:25.784 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Back on the corner of
75th and
Stewart, Tamar Manasseh is also
determined

36:25.817 --> 36:27.719 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
that change will happen.

36:27.752 --> 36:32.757 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TAMAR MANASSEH: It's going to
take a lot of
people all doing something, not
saying something,

36:32.791 --> 36:35.427 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
but doing something to fix that
problem.

36:35.460 --> 36:37.328 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And the doing something is the
sitting here.

36:37.362 --> 36:39.731 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's the sitting here, having a
conversation.

36:39.764 --> 36:41.166 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I live on this block with you.

36:41.199 --> 36:42.167 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I live in this city with you.

36:42.200 --> 36:43.668 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I live in this country with you.

36:43.701 --> 36:45.503 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And we're all affected by the
same things.

36:45.537 --> 36:49.441 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, sometimes, when we don't
talk to each
other, when we don't interact,
we miss that.

36:49.474 --> 36:55.613 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN YANG: On one corner, a
small effort in
response to a big problem.

36:55.647 --> 36:58.550 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm John
Yang in Chicago.

36:58.583 --> 37:03.988 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
